<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-24T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-24T10:00:00-05:00" n="354" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d354">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">638.5131/37: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Armour</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-24T10:00:00-05:00">February 24, 1934—10
                                    a.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>9. Your No. 13 of February 20, 1 p.m. Second paragraph. Your action is
                            approved. Is there anything in the Treaty to prevent like treatment for
                            similar American products under terms of <hi rend="italic">modus
                                vivendi.</hi></p>
                        <p>With reference to the question of the legality of putting into effect the
                            tariff reductions before ratification by the legislature, mentioned in
                            the third paragraph, this would appear to be a question for
                            determination by the Haitian Government.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>